s the sink. Use a process-level memory monitor (e.g., tracemalloc or /proc/pid/status) and assert: (a) wall-clock time is under the configured timeout, and (b) peak RSS stays below a stated memory threshold (e.g., 2× the size of a single chunk, not 1× the full file).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.18,"System":0.72,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.04}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When the S3 bucket returns a transient 503 error, the pipeline retries with exponential backoff rather than failing the entire batch.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode lives at the boundary between the pipeline orchestrator and the S3 client: the orchestrator must catch the 503 and re-invoke the S3 client with a delay. This requires wiring the two modules together; a unit test on the retry helper alone cannot confirm the orchestrator actually calls it on a 503. REAL-INFRA: A mock HTTP client that injects 503 responses is sufficient to reproduce this failure. The retry and backoff behavior is deterministic given controlled HTTP responses; real S3 is not required. MOCK-HIDE for real S3: the retry logic does not depend on S3-specific behavior beyond the HTTP status code, so a fake client that returns 503 then 200 does not hide the failure. REJECTION-GATE for System: real HTTP is not needed — the 503 can be injected in-process via a stub transport layer.","test_description":"Wire the pipeline with a fake S3 client that returns two 503 responses followed by a 200. Capture invocation timestamps. Assert: (a) the pipeline does not raise or fail the batch, (b) the S3 client is called exactly 3 times, and (c) the delay between the first and second retry is at least 2× the delay between the first call and the first retry (exponential growth). Optionally mock the sleep/timer to keep the test fast.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.12,"Integration":0.68,"System":0.18,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Rows successfully written to PostgreSQL are not duplicated if the pipeline is restarted mid-batch.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is idempotency at the database layer — whether unique constraints, upsert semantics, or a checkpoint mechanism actually prevent re-insertion when the pipeline is run twice over the same batch. This spans the pipeline writer module and the PostgreSQL driver/schema. REAL-INFRA: A real PostgreSQL instance (local test container) is required because the idempotency mechanism typically relies on PostgreSQL-specific behavior: `ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING`, serializable isolation, or advisory locks. SQLite or a mock DB will silently pass even if the real constraint is wrong or missing. REJECTION-GATE for System: a local PostgreSQL test container qualifies as Integration (local DB); no external service, real network, or OS subprocess is required beyond the DB container. The mid-batch restart can be faithfully simulated in-process by truncating processing after N rows and re-invoking the pipeline entry point.","test_description":"Using a local PostgreSQL test container, run the pipeline over a batch of 20 rows but simulate a mid-batch crash after row 10 (e.g., raise an exception in the writer). Re-run the pipeline over the full 20 rows. Query the destination table and assert that each row appears exactly once (no duplicates). Also assert that rows written before the simulated crash are present (no data loss).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.63,"System":0.32,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9796,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9796},"output_tokens":8,"ser